{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"90bd8eff-aa42-4c62-9f82-e717b0fe6a72","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>` (xUnit/NUnit) instead. This is more precise — it pins exactly which line should throw:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n\n    // Optionally assert on the exception details\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName);\n}\n```\n\n**Why:** `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line in the test throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor throwing instead of `CreateUser`). `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes the assertion to the exact call and lets you inspect the exception.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aefae0d6-1753-4e7b-ba2a-8fd767c86d57","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question — no need to explore the codebase.","outputTokens":267,"requestId":"5C2E:12F3AB:2156E2:299A27:69F5520D"},"id":"7b962cb6-6c88-4e5f-a775-32c1e0ff63bd","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:23:32.513Z","parentId":"32b7c4d8-3620-4e74-a193-c2dec1496651"}
